[1
Date: Tue 14 Aug 2001 18:32:01 -0700
From: Chuck Cooper <cc1021573@onemain.com> [edited

A Response to Michael Silvers' Comment
---------------------------------------
According to the CDC press release, [See:
<http://www.cdc.gov/od/oc/media/pressrel/r010702.htm>
_Aedes albopictus_ (AKA, tiger mosquito) is "...not widely seen in the
United States".... and... "...a species previously not seen in California."
Perhaps Michael Silvers has data they should review?
For the epidemiologically curious: The tiger mosquito is a voracious biter
and can effectively transmit many viral agents that are not normally
indigenous to Canada and the United States but are potentially harmful to
humans and animals. In addition, the mosquito can transmit viral diseases
that already exist in Canada and the U.S., such as Eastern Equine
encephalitis, Western Equine encephalitis, and La Crosse encephalitis,
which can cause disease in humans and animals.
--
Chuck Cooper
Dir. EH&S
Portland State University
<ccc@pp.pdx.edu>
